defeat.\nAmerican bus.ness has never been\nlicked. A year of price re-adjustmeat\nhas punctured a good many balloons,\nit has brought som\u00bb- hardships, it has\nhit the farmer hard, but the return to\nprosperity has been started on a -ound\nbas_s, n\u00bbton a La.-:s of inflation. The\nonly thing holding back the procession\ns the peasimurt. If he doesn\u2019t get out\nof the road and >'--n \u2019he march in the\nnext month or two he will be rudely\ntrampicd underfoot and left beh.nd\n:n i cioud of dust r.ur-ing hi- buxines-\nIn a pod of ah busine&s leader.-, au\nthorities on ec .nomics -n both the bus\niaeea worid and in the universities,\nand ail well .nformed financial editors\nof the country \u2019ak\u00bb-n by the Literary\nD.ge-t, the overwhe.-ming majority are\npos uve of bus.ness recovery in\nMarch or April. Many of the reports\nshewed that ;a many parts of the\n\u00a9oun\u2019ry the -low down in business has\nnot even been felt and some report\nbue.nebb better than, in many years.\nThe slump is not as general as many\nsupposed, in fact the whole thing has\nbeen paJnted too black\nGood times and bad t.mes are just\nthe expressions of the state of mind\nof the majority of the people. It is\nmore of psychological problem than a\nfinancial. There is a common ten\ndency or superstition that certain mys\nterious far away forces or persons are\nto blame. During the war when every\none worked hard and saved hard, pros\nerity resulted Neither Wall street\nnor the democrats could stop it. Dur\ning the war the government discov\nered 20,000.000 bond buyers where\nonly a handful had been known to ex\nist before. We 20,000,000 Liberty bond\nbuyers, we common people, are the\nbiggest force in the business of the\ncountry. By showing the same opti\nmistic spirit and industry as we did\nduring the war and by working with\na common purpose to bring about sta\nbility and normalcy, we will have pros\nperity. Do your part. Start right\naway to stir up trade. Buy something,\n\u2022ell something, keep things moving.\nGet in the front ranks in the march to\nprosperity.\nThe article In regard to drainage\nof the Sioux river bottom lands and\ntaken from the Argus-Leader, which\nappears In another column, was\nhanded to the Register for publication.\nWhile of much interest it would hardly\nseem to apply in Brookings county\nae we do not understand that an ex\npensive dam or spillway for holding\nback the water is what is needed. The\nquickest way of getting the water off\nthe land would afford relief and pre\nvent a lot of damn-lng on the part of\nthose who have been so seriously dam\naged by floods in recent years, and it\nmight be the means of restoring their\nfaith in a divine Providence.\nAccording to the FHg Stone Head\nlight- about the time a fellow gets in\ntafusterf tn the gin in fb* eorset *dver\nt\u00bbfMoment, along comes another mega\nsine with* a letter looking one Cbrset\na\u2014\ndoes\ns.\nWith capital punishment, eugenics,\nmovie censorship, university removal,\nand such urgent questions laid aside,\nwe may soon expect the legislature to\nget down to business.\n\nHYGIENIC MATING\nHendricks Pioneer\u2014-An especially\nhyg,en.< bill i now before the legist\nlature of our adjoining state South\nDakota, ami one of th' Pioneer s\nreaders aero.-- tin line, who -ays he\nlikes the paper \u201cbecause the editor\ncar: alwav- b> k lied on to .-ay sotne\nthing on almos: ev-ry -\u00fcbject,\u2019 re\npi' an opinion as \u201cthe \u25a0\u2022ubject is\n~a ng a \";\u00bb-at deal more d -cussion\nn tin i'\u25a0 ghborhood than one would\nthink.\u201d\nThe 1 .o'\u2022 ioes not wart to ap\npear to b' hanging back and imped\nng tlo m \u2022ii h of p.\u2019ogres-, but think\nsome of us are running head too fast\nami may tumble into pitfails which\nare thickly scattered along forward\nand untried paths.\nThere are, of course, people who\nui. ht not to marry; persons suffering\nof incurable and transmissable di.\nci- hit Ties and idiots, the feeble\nmind' d of a certain degree of feebb\nmindedne s, but that prohibit.on\nshould not too sweeping, for there\nis much n.on tceble mindedm -s in the\nworld than most of us suspect. We\nwould not want to bar marriage en\ntirely.\nFred'rick William of Prussia, we\nbelieve, was the first advocate of hy\ngienic mating.. He wa- going to raise\na race of giant.- from which to r* cru:\u2019\nthe Prussian guard. He succeeded\nonly in producing a brood of runts.\nSome year- ago there lived in the\nEast a family of particularly low de\ngree, densely ignorant, most of it\nmembers feeble-minded. One rnembei\nat the age of tw< nty-one could neither\nread nor write. Ten years later he\nwas a struggling lawyer, the butt of\nthe county bar, and twenty years later\nhe was a member of the president\u2019s\ncabinet.\nA little more than a century ago.\nthere wandered into a New England\ncommunity an idiot. She carried a\nbabe of a year or two. The pair was\ntaken up by the town authorities and\nsent to the poorhouse. Beneath an ap\npearance of idiocy somebody d.scov\nered in the boy something worth while.\nHe was given an opporunity to secure\nin education. Twenty years later he\nwas graduated from Yale; three years\nla-er from Andover. He became one\nof the most noted pastor< of the first\nhalf of the nineteenth century and one\nof the founder- of the most famous\nfemale coll- ze- in America. He never\nknew his own name, the name of his\nmother, and certainly not the name of\nhis father.\nWe do not mean that we should lie\nstill and let things work themselves\nout Nature expects assistance from\nher children and man has done much\nin h own way toward his evolution.\nWhen h\u00bb- has made mistakes nature\nhas corrected him. sometimes painfully\nut always kindly. She has held him\nback from the ruin into which he\nwould have precipitated himself. She\nhas also taught him the futility of\nopposing human laws to nature\u2019s laws,\nbut still some of us have not heeded\nthe lesson, but rush on with our blind\nand reckless reforming.\nW. 8. 8.\nFORGOTTEN\nSioux City Journal \u2014The plight of\nthe two Americans h*-ld prisoners ir,\na German jail because of their attempt\nto capture an infamous American\nslacker, deserter and fugitive from jus\ntice is a spectacle not to be contem\nplated with patience. The bitter cup\nof humiliation in the disgraceful Berg\ndoll ca.-e has been filled to the brim,\nand it seems that we are to be made\nto drain it to the dregs. It is not to\nbe wondered at that the prisoners\nshould feel that they have been for\ngotten by their government. Nothing\nhas been disclosed anywhere to indi\ncate that they have not been forgotten\nby the government in whose service\nPresbyterian Church\nREV. JAMES A. G. WAITS,\nYoung People\u2019s Meeting at 6:30 P. M.\n\u201cWashington the American\u201d\nThe Public is Cordially Invited to Attend These Services\nTHE BROOKINGS REGISTER, BROOKINGS, S. D., THURSDAY. FEBRUARY 17. 1921.\nSunday Q|\"|th\nFebruary MiVr\nSubject Morning Service\n\u201cThe Unfinished Race\u201d\n10:30 O\u2019clock\nSUNDAY SCHOOL AT NOON\nWITH ORCHESTRA\nCLASSES FOR ALL\nEvening Service\nAT 7:30 P. M.\nthey were when taken by the Germans.\nIf these men are not entitled to the\nprotection of their government, if they\ndo not deserve the succor of their gov\nernment, then American citizenship is\nnot worth anything. It may be that\nthe men exceeded their discretion in\nthe attempt they made to apprehend\nBergdoll, but that is not sufficient ex\ncuse for permitting them to languish\nin a German prison.\nThe lack of interest displayed by\nthe Washington government in the\nfate of these men is characteristic\nIt is a reminder of the -pineless policy\nof r)ie adininstration during the last\neight years with respect to the numer\nous murder.- of American citizens in\nMexico.\nThe Journal believes that the most\nv gorous measures -hould be employed\nto effect the releas\u00bb of the two Amer\ni ins confined at Mo-bach. It would\napprove a peremptory demand for th.\nimmediate release of the men, sup\njorted by force if necessary. The\nUnited States has an army on the\nRhine. Perhaps it ought not to b<\nthere longer, but it is there, and how\nbet'er could it be employed than in\nenforcing respect for American citi\nzenship? What is to prevent setting\nth army in motion toward Mosbach?\nIt is not a lime for timidity and legal\nhairsplitting, but for vigorous, deter\nmined action.\nThe lack of concern on the part of\nthe government in the plight of Neuf\nand Zimmer ,s more than humiliating\n-it provokes indignation. A govern\nment that will not protect its citizens\nwherev r they may bo. and especially\nits own agents deprived of their lib\nerty in the discharge of their duty\nmerits only contempt.\nw. s. s.\nFATHERS AND SONS\nMinneapolis Journal Wrapped up\nin every boy are possibilities that no\nhuman b\u00bb ng can estimate. It is well,\ntherefore, that the elders of Mimic\napolis should devote a week to taking\n.-lock of their boys, who will be the\nleaders or failures, or middle ground\ners For generations we have been\nrepeating the old saw; it is a wise\nson who knows his own father. Dur\ning that time the world has progressed\nmuch faster than our philosophy, un\ntil we may add this one: it is a wise\nfather who knows his own son.\nSound your boy right now and see\nwhat he can tell you of this lite. His\nknowledge is as varied as the con\ntent- of his pockets. He knows the\nbirds and flowers, and can tell you\nthe exact spot in which to find each\nspecie. He knows the good neighbors\nalong the street far better than you\ndo, for it is the natural instinct of a\nboy to read the heart of men. He\nalready has a working knowledge of\nmechanics, and is planning big things\nin the backyard that may some day\ndevelop to the astonishment of the j\nworld. He is natural; the heart still;\nrules his world, for he is only a step I\nfrom mother. It is only as he goes\namong men and their artificial worlds\nand false notions, that he loses h,s\nGod given naturalness.\n\u201cOnly a boy \u2014and yet tomorrow\nyou may look for him in the front\nranks of city, state and government.\nEven now he is turning over in his\nmind plans for a bigger and better\nworld to live in, than his father has\nenjoyed or suffered in.\nThe question naturally arises, what\"\nare the fathers doing to help their\nboys? Are they themselves leading\nthe best life they can; are they build\ning a name and a character that will\nlive; are they clean and honest, or\nare they only making money and gath\nering the material things of life to\nhand down to the family that follows\nafter?\nWoe betide the boy whose father\ndoes not offer him the object lesson\nof character, honor, loyalty and love.\nThese are things that are passed from\nfather to son, and which all the money\nIn the world cannot buy.\nTomorrow fathers will be leaning\non their boys. It is timely wisdom,\ntherefore, that they consider whether\nFirst\nMinister\nor not they are making them strong\nagain.-t that hour.\nW. 8. S.\nHYDROELECTRIC\nS.im-hine State\u2014\"Of the people, by\nth< people, for the people.\u201d Amend\nment I authorizing the construction oi\na hydn'-'lectric plant by the state,\nw. pted in 191 Sby a vote of 41,-\n6\u2019s 24.429.\nnot a question of increased\nThe original investment, and\nof maintenance, will be pa.d\nb> plant when in op< ration. Not\nj taXfS, but lower light, heat\nuMer bill.-, is the thing to con\n>uth Dakota pays the highe-t\ni .1 per capita of any state in\nSin pays extravagantly for\nit and power. Utilization of\n-ouri for hydro will cut the\nt two. or better, and before our\nen grow old will clear the\niiiv rent.\nWi.o will pay for delay? The pen\n;Who will gain by delay? The\nint'rests now growing fat off\npiessnees of the people. Who\n.\".ila-ing? Why this talk of\nent, when ample provision\ni \u201e.!t against excessive cost o.\nial Interest rates? Two years\nill cost the people of South\nin excess ve* ilght, heat and\nmore than they could pos\no-e if the great project were\nimmediately and the bonds\nprevailing interest rates.\nF be fooled. Nobody is foster\nn< my by opposing action on\ndr -eh etric project now. To de-\nn- only to pour more money\npockets of the people into\nr- of those who could not hold\n:.v longer if we had oud own\n\u2022on the Missouri.\nw. s. s.\nSpirit of Progress says\u2014What\ni do for your community? If a\nIs worth living in, it is cer\ny worth boosting for. Time and\n.al efforts expended in public\nk are not donations but invest\nt- which will pay good dividends\nto you whatever be your business.\nM'l- h giving money to the Chamber\nof mnierce, Y. M. C. A., Y. W. C. A.\nor oGier organizations is not reliev\ni\u2019._ your obligations to your city or\nto your community. They need and\nmust have more, they must have your\nmoral support, your boosting and your\ninterest in their affairs. A few\nhours of your personal efforts are\n<>ften times more valuable to them\nthan your money. A city is not judged\nby the number of people in it but by\nthe results obtained by those people.\nw. s. s.\nW. J Hurd of Brookings, spent sev\neral days in Brvce last week. He\ndeparted Tuesday from Brookings for\nSuperior. Neb., where he has accepted\na position as buttermaker with the\nFarmers I nion Centralizing plant.\u2014\nBruce Herald.\ny i nH nri Cjl\n/r\nBig\nI\nI\nI\nI\n1 EE\ni\ni\nI\n\ni\ni :z=\ni\n1 EE\nEE\n\nI\n\nI\nEE\ni\n\n1 EE\n1 EE\ni EE\ni\n1 e= L\nkiuaj\nc,IBENG7)\nRELIABILITY\nA great deal of this bank\u2019s reputation\nfor reliability is due to the integrity\nof its officers and directors.\nWell and favorably known; men who\nare thoroughly capable of formulating\nthe governing policies of an institu\ntion which is at all times behind the\nagricultural and mercantile develop\nment of this section.\nWe invite additional business under\nthis assurance and that of a record\nfor time tested service.\n\"Your business is